{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476162"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:41:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:41:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13657"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13657"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.86,0.01,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104528"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6262"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86855"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1641"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44158"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44911"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104528"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her parents with a history of recurrent episodes of cyanosis during feeding and crying since birth. Prenatal screening suggested a cardiac anomaly. She has no other significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, she appears mildly cyanotic, which worsens with crying. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 65/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 40/min, oxygen saturation 88%, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Auscultation reveals a harsh systolic ejection murmur at the left upper sternal border. A chest X-ray indicates a boot-shaped heart. Echocardiography confirms a large ventricular septal defect, right ventricular hypertrophy, an overriding aorta, and significant obstruction at the right ventricular outflow tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prostaglandin E1 infusion","Surgical repair","Supplemental oxygen","IV propranolol","Cardiac catheterization and balloon dilation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and diagnostic findings, including the \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E showing a boot-shaped heart and \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E confirming a large ventricular septal defect, right ventricular hypertrophy, overriding aorta, and right ventricular outflow tract obstruction, are consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003ETetralogy of Fallot\u003C/strong\u003E. Tetralogy of Fallot is a congenital heart defect characterised by four key features: a ventricular septal defect, right ventricular hypertrophy, overriding aorta, and right ventricular outflow tract obstruction. The definitive treatment is \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves patch closure of the ventricular septal defect to stop abnormal blood flow between the ventricles and resection or relief of the right ventricular outflow tract obstruction to normalize blood flow from the right ventricle to the lungs. Early surgical intervention is critical to prevent progressive heart damage and ensure normal development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstaglandin E1 infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is used to maintain ductal patency in duct-dependent cardiac conditions, which is not the primary concern in Tetralogy of Fallot. This condition does not depend on ductal patency for oxygenation or perfusion, making prostaglandin E1 infusion ineffective for the structural issues present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplemental oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is generally ineffective as a standalone treatment for the underlying cyanosis caused by the right-to-left shunt through the ventricular septal defect in Tetralogy of Fallot. While it may alleviate hypoxia temporarily, it does not rectify the primary structural abnormalities causing the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV propranolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, is sometimes used to manage acute \u0022tet spells\u0022 (short periods of time when a child\u0027s skin turns blue) by reducing heart rate and myocardial oxygen demand. However, it is not a definitive treatment for Tetralogy of Fallot and does not address the structural abnormalities that require surgical correction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac catheterization and balloon dilation\u003C/strong\u003E can provide valuable diagnostic information, and balloon dilation targets specific stenosis points such as isolated pulmonary valve stenosis. However, it does not comprehensively address the multiple defects present in Tetralogy of Fallot that require surgical correction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tetralogy of Fallot is a congenital heart defect characterised by a ventricular septal defect, right ventricular hypertrophy, overriding aorta, and right ventricular outflow tract obstruction.","Early surgical intervention in Tetralogy of Fallot is critical to prevent severe complications such as progressive heart damage and ensure normal development.","Cyanotic episodes in infants can signal underlying congenital heart defects like Tetralogy of Fallot and require immediate evaluation."],"references":["Domnina YA, Kerstein J, Johnson J, Sharma MS, Kazmerski TM, Chrysostomou C, Munoz RA. Tetralogy of Fallot. Critical Care of Children with Heart Disease: Basic Medical and Surgical Concepts. 2020:191-7.                                                                                               https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-030-21870-6_18"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86855"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13657"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86855"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T13:07:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T13:09:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6262"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104528"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data"